Analyzing Hotel Booking Data to Predict Cancelltions¶

Spring 2024 Data Science Project¶

Contributors: Tarun Thatavarthi - Solo Project

When I went to India this summer, I got to visit my uncle: who runs a chain of hotels in Chennai. Specificallly, I wanted to stay at his resort in Goa- but due to cancellations, in the 4 years since I had last visited him, he decided to close the Goa chain down: it was too much work having staff hustle around when the reservation was probably getting cancelled anyways, and he cared alot about the ease-of-life for his employees.

In the hotel business, cancellations are by far the loss-leader when it comes to the bottom line: it's a necessary evil that all owners must learn to navigate around if they want to last in the industry. For this project, our goal is to analzye hotel booking data to see if we can predict a cancellation before it happens: and save my Uncle some cash .

These are some tabs to each step of our data analysis process.

Data Collection Data Processing Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

Data Processing¶

Lets start by importing our data.

We are reading this CSV, Hotel_Bookings.csv, into a dataframe that hold all necesarry information for the rest of this tutorial.

In [143]:
df = pd.read_csv("hotel_bookings.csv")

Let's think about how a computer might see data. For example, is there any actual difference between June and July, or May and August? Computers dont necessarily understand the seasons just for their names. However, its probably easier for them to see at what interval in the year it was at. Let's convert the months into numbers.

In [144]:
month_mapping = {
    'January': 1, 'February': 2, 'March': 3, 'April': 4,
    'May': 5, 'June': 6, 'July': 7, 'August': 8,
    'September': 9, 'October': 10, 'November': 11, 'December': 12
}

df['arrival_date_month'] = df['arrival_date_month'].map(month_mapping)
df['reservation_status_date']= pd.to_datetime(df['reservation_status_date'])

With a large dataset of around 11,000 entries, we need to be careful about null values/invalid data. Let's check how much invalid data we have.

In [146]:
df.drop(['company'], axis =1, inplace = True)

Agent also seems to be relevant, at about 8-9% of our data. Let's take a look at what "agent" entails:

After looking into the dataset, these numbers are ananoymzied datapoints that represent the ID: not something we can really pull insights out of. Let's drop this as well.

In [147]:
df.drop(['agent'], axis =1, inplace = True)

When it comes to predicting whether or not a booking/vacation will end up being cancelled, there are various questions that come into play if we want to develop a system for handling them. For example I would suppose that the cheaper a booking is, the more likely it is to be cancelled.

For this question, lets adopt hypothesis testing:

I would assume that there is a statisfically signifant correlation between booking price and cancellation status, ie: The price of a vacation is direcrtly related to whether it will be cancelled or not. Let's test this:

We'll use Levene's test to examine the potential interplay between months, booking changes, and cancellations. The reason we are comparing booking changes is to try and see seasonality/season volatility, when many people are hecticly planning and things change. This can introduce volatility and irregularties in our dataset, that if somehwat ordered, we may need to structure our models around. This analysis aims to determine if these factors are actually connected. While prices might independently influence cancellations, we're interested in discerning if seasonality or holiday volatility plays a role. If Levene's test reveals significant associations among months, booking changes, and cancellations, it suggests a unique insight into how hotel managers can strategize for specific time periods.

In [159]:
stat_adr, p_adr = levene(*[group['adr'] for name, group in df.groupby('arrival_date_month')])
print('Levenes test for adr (Statistic: {:.3f}, P-value: {:.3f})'.format(stat_adr, p_adr))

# Levene's test for equality of variances in booking_changes
stat_bc, p_bc = levene(*[group['booking_changes'] for name, group in df.groupby('arrival_date_month')])
print('Levenes test for booking changes (Statistic: {:.3f}, P-value: {:.3f})'.format(stat_bc, p_bc))

# Decision based on Levene's test
if p_adr > 0.05 and p_bc > 0.05:
    print("Variances are equal across groups. Proceed with ANOVA.")
else:
    print("Variances are not equal. Consider using transformations or non-parametric tests.")

Looks like it does, and by a huge margin. However, just checking these numbers is not enough. Let's do a chi-quare test to see if there is in general a correlation between countries and cancellations.

Why do a Chi-Square test?

A chi-square test is the test of choice for seeing whether one variable relates to changes in another variable, specfically it can help idenfity if some changes are due to change or if they are due to just happenstance.

As a quick intutiive way to udnerstand it, it measure the difference between if we observed the frequencies of data assuming the variables were related, contrasted to if we observe the data assuming there is NO correlation. Here is a short youtube video that gets the point across:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7_cs1YlZoug

In [165]:

Let's look at the numbers: that number in speicifc is huge: it reprsents teh difference between no-correlation ie assuming correlation: meaning for our suggestion that country andd cancellations are related, this is a great indicator. But how do we know whether this is by chance or not?

As we covered before in this tutorial, the P value once again shows that this is not really a chance or coincedence, that this relation is real and is actually pretty strong. We can also do a Z test like we did last time to confirm this.

Seems like the answer is OVERWHELIMINGLY YES. Now, let's check out if Portugal in specific is an indicator of a possible cancellation.

Model Development, Testing¶

Now it's time to actually develop out models and see how well they work. Luckily, we dont really have to do these from scratch, as the SKLearn library already has great implementations of these models that we can just use on the dataset we have curated.

You should be proud of yourself, we cleaned up the dataset and made sure it is compatible with these models: we have alot of power in our hands now.

Let's start with Logistic Regression. What is it? To keep it short, it works the way any of our equations in algebra do: we have a Dependent variable and then a certain amount of predictor variables that go into an equation to determine whether something can be classified one way or not. The way that this model trains, is that for every data point it makes a guess, and it tries to optimize its guess to be correct. It adjusts it's weights for predictor variables to try and be correct as much as possible. As such it's prone to overfitting since its literaly jsut adjusting to the numbers in a dataset. However, it's a good start.

I'll only repeat this once because the SKLearn Machine Learning models are prettty simple to use. Because we have done the dirty work of setting up and partitioning the data, all we have to dois just call.fit to fir the data/train it, and then .predict to predict for our entire test dataset. Then, we can compare our predictions to the actual values for the various metrics we want.

Now, let's take a look at a new type of Model: K Nearest Neighbors.

Let's imagine you can plot a point on a graph. Now imagine plotting a bunch of points on a graph. At a very basic level, the closer two points are, the more similar they are! It's with that same logic, that even if multiple 3d spaces, that we can plot points based on all their data and then check for the nearest neighborhs to see how similar they are. The K is the amount of neighbors we consdier: and we go with the majority class to classify it. Let's see what our scores look like:

With recall around 76^ for our postitives, it shows that the model is not really overfitting, and may have found a healthy balance to generally understand the classifcation criteria. Aditionally, an overall accuracy of 86% is stellar. Let's analyze why this might be later on.

Whenever we want to classify thinks we often ask questions. For example, if I told you someone played a sports and you needed to figure out which sport, you would probably ask:

Are they tall?

Are they Slow? Are they Fast?

How much do they weight?

What's the strongest part of their body?

And as I answerwed these questions, you could be like "oh they are tall, fast, light, and their legs are strong, they probably play basketball!"

Or, you could be like:

"Oh they are short, slow, and their arms are strong. They must powerlift!".

This is how decision trees work. They organize the data by their most differentiating characteristivs, and move down a tree to eventually hit a end point where they have decided what classification they are. Here is a visual representation:

As a result, we need to be a little more picky about BLAH BLAH BLAH:

The performance of our tree is withheld because deicions are made outside of the context of each other: we need a model that considers everything more holistically.

Breaking down all of our models performance and variations, it's clear that K nearest neighborghs is the best option for prediciting cancellations by a prety wide margin. But why is that?

  1. Dimensionality: KNN is a way to basically plot points in space and see which points are most similar by proximity: by cleaning the data properly and seeing whether or not something actually resembles the "situation" of a reservation, we are able to get more accurate depictions of what "might" happen- hence why the model performed so strongly. This is something that both linear regressin and decision trees lack and lets go through each one:

  2. In the case of the linear regression, its possible that the clasification boundrarary for what actually makes a reservation more likely to cancel isnt very linear: in real life, this makes sense. There are alot of factors and correlations that go into somebody deciding to finally cancel a booking. While linear regression can clearly estimate this chance on some level, KNN is much more able to contextualize a data point in comparison to other ones.

  3. Aditionally, there is alot of ordinality in this dataset whether we like it or not, those may have had a huge influence in the regressions decisions when attending to certain values, where KNN is may have been able to actually group situations together, linear regresssion kind of just pushes the model to belive something is true, and not much other influence is taken into consideration.

  4. In the case of a decision tree, I personally believe that this approach is inherently flawed: decision trees are higly prone to overfitting,and with a dataset as varied and also large as this one, overfitting for certain fluctuations may have led the model to ahve subpar performance. The tree is inehrently just a reprsentation of the dataset, and with larger depth the performance was only marginally getting better, represetnaive that the structure itself does not suit itself to a problem asmulti-facedted as this one, especially when certain values are not actually related to one another. With KNN, these values get implcitly grouped together, but in actual priroty that makes sene becuse they are all hosted in an actual space, not a graph.

Insights and Conclusions¶

For some short conclusions after analzying everything here are important things we observed:

  1. For hotel bookings, dimensionality / non linearity seems to be important to getting a better understanding/world view of the imformation itself.

  2. Portugal is not a good place to start a hotel business compared to the rest of the world, they see by far the most cancellations and incosistent booking.

  3. Linear regression is a decent tool for getting a quick judgements, if you possibly do not have alot of computing power/need to streamline the process.
